# Topic 5 (CSS track): Advanced CSS Styling (Roadmap Checklist)

## Level 1 — Beginner: State-based and generated styling

- [ ] **Understand the problem pseudo-classes solve.** Plain selectors can only target elements based on what's permanently true about them (tag, class, ID) — but a lot of real UI needs to respond to *temporary state*: is the mouse currently over this button? Does this input currently have keyboard focus? Pseudo-classes let CSS target these transient states directly, without needing JavaScript to add/remove a class every time the state changes.
- [ ] **Learn the three foundational interaction pseudo-classes:** `:hover` (true while the pointer is over the element), `:focus` (true while the element has keyboard or click focus — critical for accessibility, since it's the *only* visual signal a keyboard-only user gets about where they currently are on the page), and `:nth-child(n)` (selects an element based on its numeric position among its siblings, regardless of tag type).
- [ ] **Revisit `::before`/`::after` with their actual requirement spelled out:** a pseudo-element only renders if it has a `content` property set — even `content: "";` (an empty string) — because without `content`, there's nothing for the browser to actually generate. These exist to let you add small decorative or structural content (icons, shapes, tooltip arrows) without cluttering your real HTML with elements that have no semantic meaning.
- [ ] **Learn `transition` as "smooth interpolation between two states," nothing more.** By default, when a CSS property's value changes (say, `:hover` changes a button's background color), the browser applies the new value instantly. `transition: background-color 0.2s ease;` tells the browser to animate that specific change over 0.2 seconds instead of snapping to it — transitions only ever describe how to get from an old value to a new one; they don't create the change itself.
- [ ] **Learn the correct order for link pseudo-classes, and why order matters here specifically:** `:link`, `:visited`, `:hover`, `:active` (often remembered as "LVHA") must be declared in that order, because they can have equal specificity, and the cascade's "last rule wins" tiebreaker would otherwise silently make a later rule (like `:visited`) override an earlier one (like `:hover`) regardless of which state is actually currently true.
- [ ] **Avoid the classic beginner accessibility mistake: removing the default focus outline without replacing it.** `outline: none;` on `:focus` makes a page look "cleaner" to a mouse user but makes it literally unnavigable for a keyboard-only user, who now has no visual indication of where they are at all — if you remove the default outline, you must replace it with an equally visible custom focus style.
- [ ] **Hands-on:** style a button with distinct `:hover`, `:focus`, and `:active` states using only a background-color `transition`, then tab to it using only the keyboard (no mouse) to confirm the focus state is genuinely visible.

## Level 2 — Intermediate: Precise selection, multi-step animation, and form UX

- [ ] **Learn the `:nth-child(an+b)` formula precisely**, not just the common shorthand cases like `:nth-child(odd)`/`:nth-child(even)` — `a` is the cycle size, `b` is the offset, so `:nth-child(3n+1)` selects the 1st, 4th, 7th, etc. child. Crucially, **`:nth-child` counts among *all* sibling elements regardless of tag**, while `:nth-of-type` counts only among siblings of the *same tag* — mixing these up is a very common source of "why did it select the wrong element" bugs when siblings aren't all the same type.
- [ ] **Learn the broader pseudo-class toolkit:** `:not(selector)` excludes elements matching its argument, `:first-child`/`:last-child` target edge positions, `:checked` targets a checked checkbox/radio, `:disabled` targets disabled form controls, and `:focus-within` is true on a *parent* element when any descendant inside it currently has focus — useful for highlighting an entire form group when one of its inputs is active.
- [ ] **Understand the real distinction between transitions and animations, from first principles.** A transition is fundamentally reactive and two-state: it needs something else (a hover, a class toggle) to trigger a change from an existing value to a new one, and it only ever knows about a "before" and "after." An `@keyframes` animation, applied via the `animation` property, is self-running and multi-step: you can define any number of intermediate states (`0%`, `50%`, `100%`, etc.) and control looping (`animation-iteration-count`), direction (`animation-direction`), and what happens before/after it runs (`animation-fill-mode`) — animations don't need an external trigger event the way transitions do.
- [ ] **Learn timing functions as descriptions of rate-of-change over time, not arbitrary presets.** `linear` moves at a constant speed (which often looks robotic for UI motion); `ease`, `ease-in`, `ease-out`, and `ease-in-out` accelerate/decelerate at different points; `cubic-bezier()` lets you define a fully custom curve. The first-principles reason `ease-out` tends to feel more natural for things "arriving" on screen: real physical objects decelerate as they settle, so a curve that slows toward the end matches intuitive expectations better than constant speed.
- [ ] **Style forms using validation-state pseudo-classes:** `:valid` and `:invalid` reflect the browser's built-in Constraint Validation API result (covered in the HTML Forms topic) directly in CSS, letting you visually flag a field as soon as its value satisfies or violates its own validation attributes — without writing any JavaScript to check it yourself.
- [ ] **Learn the correct technique for custom-styled checkboxes/radios.** Visually hiding the native input with `display: none` also removes it from the accessibility tree, breaking screen reader and keyboard support entirely. The standard approach instead visually hides the native input in a way that keeps it focusable and announced (commonly via clipping/opacity tricks rather than `display: none`), then builds the custom visual appearance alongside it using `::before`/`::after` or a sibling element tied to its `:checked` state.

## Level 3 — Expert: Performance, accessibility nuance, and real-world rigor

- [ ] **Understand exactly why some animated properties are cheap and others are expensive.** Animating `transform` or `opacity` can often be handled entirely by the GPU compositor, skipping layout and paint recalculation altogether. Animating properties like `width`, `top`, `left`, or `margin` forces the browser to recompute layout on every single frame of the animation — which is why professional-grade animations are almost always built using `transform`/`opacity` even when something like `top`/`left` would seem more intuitive for movement.
- [ ] **Understand `will-change` as a targeted hint, not a free performance boost.** It tells the browser "this property is about to be animated, prepare accordingly" (e.g., promoting the element to its own compositor layer in advance), but applying it broadly or permanently can actually *increase* memory usage by creating layers that are never needed — it's meant to be applied narrowly, right before an animation starts, not as a blanket optimization.
- [ ] **Understand the precise difference between `:focus` and `:focus-visible`, and why it exists.** `:focus` matches *any* focus event, including a mouse click on a button (which doesn't visually need a focus ring, since the user can already see what they clicked). `:focus-visible` uses browser heuristics to match only the cases where a focus indicator is actually *useful* — primarily keyboard navigation — letting you show a focus ring for keyboard users without forcing an often-unwanted ring on every mouse click.
- [ ] **Treat `prefers-reduced-motion` as a non-optional accessibility consideration, not a nice-to-have.** Some users have vestibular disorders or motion sensitivity where animation can cause real physical discomfort, and have explicitly set this preference at the OS level. Wrapping non-essential animations in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) { ... }` and providing a near-instant alternative respects that choice — the first-principles point being that motion design should never assume it's universally welcome.
- [ ] **Know a genuine specificity surprise: `:not(selector)` is not specificity-free.** Many people assume `:not()` adds zero specificity since it's "just an exclusion," but it actually contributes the specificity of whatever selector is *inside* it — `:not(.foo)` carries the specificity of a class selector, which can unexpectedly out-rank a plain element selector you didn't think it was competing with.
- [ ] **Know how to diagnose janky animations using browser tooling**, not guesswork: the Performance panel reveals whether frames are dropping and why, and Chrome's "Paint flashing" / Layers panel reveal exactly which regions are repainting on every frame — turning "this feels laggy" into a concrete, fixable layout-vs-paint-vs-composite diagnosis.
- [ ] **Combine CSS custom properties with `@keyframes` for themeable, dynamic animations** — defining a keyframe animation in terms of `var(--accent-color)` or a custom property controlled by JavaScript lets the same animation definition adapt to different themes or states without duplicating the whole `@keyframes` block.
- [ ] **Know that the View Transitions API exists as the newer, more powerful evolution of this whole space** — enabling smooth, animated transitions between completely different DOM states (including full page navigations) using a higher-level browser API rather than hand-rolled transition/animation choreography — worth knowing exists even if it's beyond what you need right now.
- [ ] **Hands-on:** build a custom checkbox that remains fully keyboard-accessible and screen-reader-announced; build a multi-step `@keyframes` loading spinner; toggle your OS's "reduce motion" setting and confirm your `prefers-reduced-motion` media query actually responds to it; open DevTools' Performance panel on a deliberately janky `width`-animated element and compare it against the same animation rewritten with `transform`.

## Quick self-check before moving on

You should be able to explain, without looking anything up: why transitions need a trigger but animations don't, why `nth-child` and `nth-of-type` can select different elements on the exact same markup, why animating `transform` is cheaper than animating `width`, why `:focus-visible` exists separately from `:focus`, and why respecting `prefers-reduced-motion` is an accessibility requirement rather than a stylistic choice.